## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core/.NET 5+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — the entire abort model is gone
3. The cooperative cancellation model (`CancellationToken`) replaces thread abort

### Why Thread.Abort Was Removed

`Thread.Abort` was always dangerous — it could corrupt shared state by injecting `ThreadAbortException` at arbitrary points (mid-write, mid-lock, etc.). .NET Core replaced it with **cooperative cancellation**, which is safer but requires the work to opt in.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST observe the CancellationToken for
    /// timeout to actually halt execution.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            // If the task doesn't complete in time, this throws.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result unwraps AggregateException for faulted tasks.
        // If work threw, this rethrows wrapped in AggregateException —
        // matching the original behavior.
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw task.Exception!;   // AggregateException

        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in modern .NET code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must accept and observe the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        // Option A: pass token to APIs that support it
        return db.ExecuteQuery(query, ct);

        // Option B: poll in loops
        // while (!ct.IsCancellationRequested) { ... }
        // ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work ignores token** | If `work` never checks `ct`, it runs to completion even after timeout. The caller gets `TimeoutException`, but the work is still running on a thread pool thread — a **fire-and-forget leak**. |
| **`Thread.Abort` in libraries** | Any dependency calling `Thread.Abort` will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime with no compile error. Audit with: `grep -r "Thread.Abort\|ResetAbort"`. |
| **`Task.Result` vs `.GetAwaiter()`** | `Task.Result` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`. If you want the raw exception, use `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` instead. |
| **Sync-over-async deadlocks** | The sync `ExecuteWithTimeout` calls `task.Wait()`. In UI/ASP.NET contexts with a `SynchronizationContext`, this can deadlock. Prefer the async overload. |
| **`default(T)` change** | Not an issue here, but nullable reference types in .NET 8 will warn about `T result = default` — the new pattern avoids this entirely by returning `task.Result`. |
